BACKGROUND

Software has become a powerful leveraging agent in the US economy. It is a
preeminent integrating element upon which many other critical technologies are
leveraged and depend. It is the ultimate green technology and agent of change.
It drives deep structural changes in the global economy through relentless
automation and augmentation of mental tasks, much as the industrial
revolution of the previous century transformed society through the
automation of physical tasks.

In short, software has become a crucial national resource, vital to the
well-being and competitiveness of the country.  In occupying this pivotal
role, the software sector faces important challenges:

     Achieving societal requirements for quality and reliability in
     critical software systems.

     Maintaining a strong defense largely dependent on complex,
     embedded software systems.

     Educating and training the current and future software
     workforce.

     Avoiding market and job losses from foreign competition.

     Establishing effective standards to guide development of ever-
     larger systems and networks.

     Protecting intellectual property and preventing software
     piracy.

     Promoting software research, investment, and trade.

     Ensuring competitiveness in the global marketplace.

     Developing a National Information Infrastructure and other
     21st century systems.


All of these challenges raise national issues that must be addressed in a
coherent and effective manner.

Origins of the National Software Council

The National Software Council was conceived as a response to the growing need
to address software issues of national importance. The NSC concept was
developed in 1993 at a USAF-sponsored workshop attended by software leaders
from academia, industry, and defense, under the guidance and vision of
Mr. Lloyd Mosemann.  A principal finding of the workshop was that software
had become a true national resource vital to the economy, and that a
national-level council was required to help shape public policy to ensure
its continued growth and vitality.

An NSC task force was organized to foster national advocacy and support for
the concept.  The final report of the task force recommended that the National
Security Industrial Association create an Implementation Committee composed
of members representative of the software community to proceed with
formation of the NSC.

In order to accomplish these tasks the Software and Information Systems
Committee (SISC) is organizing this Fall '94 workshop. The workshop will bring
interested parties together from a broad spectrum of society (industry,
government, and academia), present these persons with appropriate information
about the necessity for a NSC, explain the role of the NSC Implementation
Committee (NSC-IC), identify resource commitments that will be required,
and culminate in a nominating and/or voting process to organize the NSC
implementation committee.

The workshop has two objectives:

(1) Refine the key software issues that necessitate a NSC

(2) Organize the NSC Implementation Committee

